Bethany Weber Hannah is with Christian Hannah.
July 30 at 10:55 AM ·

This is so cool.... if you have kids, you should check it out. You can see different animals in 3-d using your phone camera (augmented reality).
Directions:
1. Go to google.com
2. Search the animal you would like (lion, shark, etc. )
3. Scroll down until you see the words “View in 3-d” and click that.
4. You might have to click View in your space.
5. Then it should pop up in your camera.

post_text:
We did it! We exercised enough miles as a school over the last two weeks that we made it to both Disney World AND Disneyland! 3,491 total miles! Wow! We almost didn't get there yesterday, but just made it with a couple of late entries logged in. Great job everyone!
Hopefully, everyone has enjoyed getting out with their families and taking extra walks, bike rides, and runs and we keep this great health habit up. The more we exercise, the better we feel and the healthier we are!
Follow this link to see a slideshow: https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/1cXvKIAbgkxrRk3Xv6wsjbIAnMxyTRGXOrJe5lUjhAzI/edit?usp=sharing
and enjoy the Mickey's Mix Magic Fireworks at Disneyland as a celebration of our hard work!
https://youtu.be/94sPdEY7OGU

post_text: Mrs. Weinert to the Class of 2020.
text: Mrs. Weinert to the Class of 2020.

post_text:
We are so close to making it to both Disney World AND Disneyland on our two-week trip! Only 300 miles to go! We made it to the Grand Canyon in Arizona. We have put in a lot of exercise miles as a school, but I think we can do a little extra today so we can get there. This is the last day to count those miles. Enjoy this beautiful weather today and put those miles in!

2nd grade and their families have taken a lead in miles, but I really saw some of the other grades add in some miles this weekend (hello 8th grade!). Let's all work hard to tally those miles up today and get us to Disneyland! We can do it together! Go Elsinboro!

post_text: Ms. Nelson to the Class of 2020.
text: Ms. Nelson to the Class of 2020.

post_text:
We are now halfway across the country! 1, 973 miles and counting. We took an overnight stop in San Antonio!

Can't wait to see how far we can go as we continue on. Since I don't update on the weekend, I am going to keep it open until Monday! Can we make it to the west coast by then?! The staff certainly thinks so, and they keep logging those miles. Let's all put in as many miles as we can between now and then! We've got this!

For a little extra inspiration, let's check out one of Mrs. Lockwood's favorite rides, and a classic ride at both Disney World and Disneyland, Big Thunder Mountain! https://youtu.be/ZmmteiM_K1Q

post_text: Mrs. Hannah to the Class of 2020
text: Mrs. Hannah to the Class of 2020

post_text:
We are now 1,644 miles into our trip and have made it to New Orleans! New Orleans is world-renowned for its distinct music, Creole cuisine, unique dialect, and its annual celebrations and festivals, most notably Mardi Gras.

2nd grade is the first grade to get 100% participation, great job! The staff is still leading the way with 449 miles, but K and their families are catching up! Let's all get out and really put in some miles today!

This last weekend hopefully you got to watch the SpaceX launch, the first shuttle from an American launch site since 2011. While watching, did you wonder what it is like to be an astronaut? You’ll find out on Mrs. Kretzer's favorite Disney ride Mission: SPACE!
https://youtu.be/ldOPeg4KGqw

We are now 1, 424 total miles into our trip! I am so impressed at how hard everyone is working to rack up those miles! We made it to Disney and kept on going! We are working our way west and are now in Mobile, Alabama.
I think we have some competitors on our staff, the staff has now taken the lead in miles. What grade is going to step up to the challenge and see if they can be the leaders in the school?!

image.png

2nd grade now leads the way with the most participation. 8th grade- where are yooooouuuu?! (If you need an extra incentive, you have to exercise at least once this week to get your grade!). Since 2nd grade is leading the way, let's check out our second-grade teacher's favorite ride. Mrs. Hannah loves the Dinosaur Ride. Hold on tight for a turbulent journey as you travel back in time on a perilous prehistoric race to rescue a dinosaur—before the meteor strikes!
https://youtu.be/ZHNZUPUJyGI

post_text:
Wow!! We made it to Disney yesterday and kept on going! Celebrate by enjoying this Wishes celebration at Disney World, one of Mrs. McAllister's and Mrs. Morgan's favorites. No one puts on a fireworks, light and music show quite like Disney! https://youtu.be/rTO1RlF12ZU.

We are now 284 miles west and we are going to keep on going and see how far we can make it across the country by Friday. Think we can make it to CA?! We will need everyone to do it! So let's make it a little competition! Right now, 7th grade has the highest percentage of their class participating, followed closely by 2nd grade. 8th, 4th, and 5th graders where are you? Let's get everyone moving!
image.png

We can also look at who is contributing the most miles. 6th graders and their families are leading the way, but only by a tiny amount over Kindergarten and their families and all the staff and their families. I've already finished a 3.5-mile run this morning and am headed out for a walk with my husband. What will you do today to help us grow our miles?
image.png

post_text:
We are almost there! Just over 40 miles to go! We have made it to Daytona Beach, FL! I think we can easily get there today, and if we do, we will keep on going and see if we can make it to Disneyland in CA! I am so impressed by all the hard work and miles we have put in and how quickly we got to FL!
Today check out the Hall of Presidents! It is Mrs. Lombardi's favorite show at Disney World, and one of the original shows there. It uses audio- animatronics and was originally created as "Great Moments with Mr. Lincoln" for the 1964 World's Fair which was groundbreaking technology at the time. For Disney World, they expanded it to include all the presidents, and it is updated each time we elect a new president.
https://youtu.be/mD91VpIWlYo
Keep updating those miles, and remember that one entry can be used for all family members that day!

text:
We are almost there! Just over 40 miles to go! We have made it to Daytona Beach, FL! I think we can easily get there today, and if we do, we will keep on going and see if we can make it to Disneyland in CA! I am so impressed by all the hard work and miles we have put in and how quickly we got to FL!
Today check out the Hall of Presidents! It is Mrs. Lombardi's favorite show at Disney World, and one of the original shows there. It uses audio- animatronics and was originally created as "Great Moments with Mr. Lincoln" for the 1964 World's Fair which was groundbreaking technology at the time. For Disney World, they expanded it to include all the presidents, and it is updated each time we elect a new president.
https://youtu.be/mD91VpIWlYo
Keep updating those miles, and remember that one entry can be used for all family members that day!

YOUTUBE.COM
The History of & Changes to The Hall of Presidents | Magic Kingdom

Wow! We are really moving!

Today check out the Tower of Terror- Mrs. Boyle's favorite ride! The plot of The Twilight Zone Tower of Terror follows the tragic night of Oct. 31, 1939, when lightning struck the building. Five people were aboard an elevator as the building was struck, causing the elevator to free-fall. The Hollywood closed following these events, but has reopened, allowing new guests to experience these haunting events. Hold on tight!
https://youtu.be/_w_pilK1ncg

Keep recording your miles! Don't forget to record all family members in one entry, don't do a repeat of the miles! https://forms.gle/LpikJzz9fMNcGcqu8

post_text:
Are you a roller coaster rider?! Check out a front seat view of Mrs. McAllister's, Mrs. Simms', and Mr. Sarbello's favorite ride at Disney!
The riders board the roller coaster in the model village of Serka Zong, to begin a speedy route through the Himalayas to the base of Mount Everest. On the way up it passes through a ransacked temple with murals of the yeti, warning the riders that the mountain is his territory. At the top of the mountain the train curves around the main peak and goes through a cave. When it emerges, it draws to a halt in front of track that has been torn apart by the yeti. That's when things really get started!
The teachers have already started putting their miles in on our way to Disney, make sure you do the same! Let's see how fast we can get there!!
https://youtu.be/dW5plLrebUg

post_text:
A dangerous and effective new scam is telling New Jersey residents that they need to provide their bank account information via phone, email, or social media message in order to "receive" their $1,200 federal stimulus check.

If a person calls, emails, or messages you and tells you that you need to give them your bank account information in order to receive your stimulus check or to receive it more quickly, they are lying. You do not need to provide any additional information to any caller or emailer in order to receive these funds.

For more REAL information go here
https://www.consumer.ftc.gov/blog/2020/04/want-get-your-coronavirus-relief-check-scammers-do-too?utm_source=govdelivery

post_text: Dear Elsinboro Parents/Guardians, A message from Governor Murphy regarding school closure. We will continue to update you as more information becomes available. Be Safe. We miss you all so much.
shared_text:
Governor Phil Murphy
March 26 at 2:07 PM ·

Let me be clear: The decision to reopen school districts rests with me. We will not be prepared to revisit the closure until at least April 17th, at the very earliest.

The decision to reopen will be based on careful discussion with our public health and safety experts, and with our educators and districts. We will be guided by the facts on the ground.

Coronavirus Rumor Control

FEMA maintains a rumor control page to help the public distinguish between rumors and facts regarding the response to Coronavirus (COVID-19). Rumors can easily circulate within communities during a crisis, stay informed and please get your information from credible sources.

👉Learn more at https://www.fema.gov/coronavirus-rumor-control

🖥️Visit https://www.nj.gov/health/

‪Remember – don’t let fear overtake facts. Stay informed.

Elsinboro School was visited by the Blue Rocks' Rocky Bluewinkle to learn about Rocky's Reading Challenge. This program is designed to show kids that reading can be both fun and rewarding while using the Blue Rocks brand to increase literacy in our community!
Students are encouraged to read ten (10) books, and if they do so, they receive two (2) free tickets to a Blue Rocks game!
Students had a great time reading with Rocky!

post_text: Kindergarten had a fantastic 100th day of school. We did 100-themed centers and activities, read books and wrote about 100, and even had a 100th Day Fashion Show!
text: Kindergarten had a fantastic 100th day of school. We did 100-themed centers and activities, read books and wrote about 100, and even had a 100th Day Fashion Show!

post_text: 8th Grade students “worked” in a water treatment plant in their study of Humans, their impact on ecosystems and biodiversity. Students aerated water, added a food additive to coagulate the pollution, let it all settle, and built their own filters out of sand, pebbles and coffee filters.
text: 8th Grade students “worked” in a water treatment plant in their study of Humans, their impact on ecosystems and biodiversity. Students aerated water, added a food additive to coagulate the pollution, let it all settle, and built their own filters out of sand, pebbles and coffee filters.

post_text: Second graders celebrated the 100th day of school by completing many activities that involved the number 100. They read and wrote 100 words, jumped for 100 seconds, stacked 100 cups, rolled a die to 100, measured 100 inches, feet, and yards, made a 100 dot picture, completed 100 addition and subtraction facts, found 100 Roman numerals, and more.
text: Second graders celebrated the 100th day of school by completing many activities that involved the number 100. Congratulations to the following students who had their "Creative Creatures" 100-word stories published. This writing contest was from the spring, 2019.

Gianna, Jasmyne, Brianna, Kya, Hannah and Ryann!

Congratulations to the following students who had their "Spooky Saga" 100-word stories published from the writing contest in the fall, 2019.

Katarina, Kya, Jasmyne, Kamryn, Ryann, Melissa, Brianna, Julliana, Kylie, Hannah, Gianna, Michael, Olivia, Autumn, Ray, Laila, Morgan, Ava, Jaxson and Jayden.

Over 10,000 students entered these contests and our Elsinboro students surely represented Elsinboro well! Congratulations to all students. You make us proud! Can't wait to see if we have any winners in the February 2020 "Once Upon a Dream" poetry contest! Good luck!

post_text: 6th grade just completed reading the book “The Egypt Game” and creating a classroom library book titled “Egypt A to Z." We have learned about Pharaohs, Mummies, Kings/Queens and even dung beetles! You could say we learned everything “A to Z." Today, we ended this unit by creating mummification mixtures to see which combination will best mummify apples. Next week, we will analyze and record our results and using the best mixture, we will create our own mummy faces! Stay tuned for our results and more pictures.

post_text:
FYI:
A quarterly test of the Salem/Hope Creek Nuclear Generating Stations Alert and Notification system on Tuesday, January 7, 2020. The sirens will sound at around 10:45 a.m.

The 37 sirens located within ten miles of the Salem/Hope Creek, NJ plants will be activated for 3 to 5 minutes. The siren tests will be followed by a test message of the Emergency Alert System on local radio stations.

Sirens that will be tested are the same sirens used to alert the public in the event of an actual emergency at either the Salem or Hope Creek Nuclear Generating Stations. In such an emergency, the public would be alerted by the sirens to tune their radios to one of the local EAS stations for important emergency instructions.
text:
FYI:
A quarterly test of the Salem/Hope Creek Nuclear Generating Stations Alert and Notification system on Tuesday, January 7, 2020. The sirens will sound at around 10:45 a.m.

The 37 sirens located within ten miles of the Salem/Hope Creek, NJ plants will be activated for 3 to 5 minutes. The siren tests will be followed by a test message of the Emergency Alert System on local radio stations.

Sirens that will be tested are the same sirens used to alert the public in the event of an actual emergency at either the Salem or Hope Creek Nuclear Generating Stations. In such an emergency, the public would be alerted by the sirens to tune their radios to one of the local EAS stations for important emergency instructions.
